psycopg — PostgreSQL database adapter for Python
------------------------------------------------

  Component:   psycopg (v3), including its implementation packages
               psycopg-c (production image) and psycopg-binary (local dev).
  Version:     >= 3.1, < 4.0
  License:     GNU Lesser General Public License v3.0 only (SPDX: LGPL-3.0-only)
  Upstream:    https://www.psycopg.org/  ·  https://github.com/psycopg/psycopg
  License text: licenses/LGPL-3.0.txt (LGPL-3.0 incorporates the terms of the
               GNU GPL v3.0, included as licenses/GPL-3.0.txt).

  Why it is included, and the obligations we satisfy:

  psycopg is LGPL-3.0 — the one copyleft dependency in the tree, permitted
  deliberately. It is *dynamically imported* by an application (TruePPM is not a
  library that statically incorporates it), so under the LGPL's library-linking
  terms it does not affect the license of TruePPM's own code, and it is
  compatible with both the Apache-2.0 Community Edition and the proprietary
  Enterprise edition. We do not modify psycopg's source.

  LGPL-3.0 §4 (combined works) requires that recipients be able to relink or
  replace the covered library. TruePPM satisfies this **by construction**:

    * psycopg is installed from PyPI as a normal, replaceable wheel in
      site-packages — never frozen into a single-file binary or statically
      linked into a blob. An operator can `pip install` a different psycopg
      build (including in vendored or air-gapped deployments) without rebuilding
      TruePPM.
    * The production Docker image installs the `psycopg[c]` implementation,
      which dynamically links the C extension against the **system** libpq
      (libpq5) rather than bundling its own. This is a security-posture choice,
      not an additional §4 lever: OS-level libpq/OpenSSL upgrades to the base
      image flow through to the driver. The §4 relink guarantee above is over
      psycopg itself and is satisfied identically by either implementation —
      both `[c]` and `[binary]` are replaceable site-packages wheels — while
      libpq is permissively licensed (PostgreSQL License) and carries no
      copyleft relink obligation. (Local development uses the precompiled
      `psycopg[binary]` wheel for convenience; it bundles its own libpq and is
      not used in production.)

  Operator note: if you build a deliberately *frozen* or *vendored* derivative
  that embeds psycopg as a static/single-file artifact, the §4 relink obligation
  becomes yours to satisfy — keep psycopg a replaceable component, or ship the
  object code/relink materials with your derivative. The stock TruePPM images do
  not do this, so no extra step is required for them.
